<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Government Statements): Retirees able to defer
annuities until rates rise - Personal pensions
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Members of a tax-approved personal pension scheme will be allowed to defer
purchasing an annuity at pension date, if they wish, until age 75. They will
also be able to withdraw amounts during the deferral period which are
broadly equivalent to the annuity that their fund could have provided.
The changes will take effect after Royal assent is given to the finance
bill.
Under the tax rules an annuity must be purchased when any benefit is taken
from a personal pension fund. This means that people who retire when annuity
rates are low may have to buy a considerably smaller annuity than they could
have done with the same fund if they had been able to postpone purchase
until annuity rates were more favourable.
Under the proposed measures, personal pension scheme members who defer
purchasing an annuity will be able to make income withdrawals in the
deferral period broadly equivalent to the annuity that their fund could have
provided. Income withdrawals will be reviewed every three years to ensure
the pension fund is not too rapidly depleted.
Investment income and capital gains will continue to build up tax-free
during the deferral period.
The proposed measures will apply whether or not members elect to take the
tax-free lump sum at pension date.
Amendments are proposed to allow the trustees or managers of approved
pension schemes to purchase annuities from certain insurance companies
established in other European Union countries.
One of the ways that tax-approved occupational and personal pension schemes
provide benefits is by securing pensions through the purchase of an annuity
from a life insurance company.
At present the tax rules limit annuities to those provided by UK-authorised
insurers. The Third Life Insurance Directive creates a single market in
insurance products throughout the EU.
Under the Budget proposal, the range of insurance companies that can provide
annuities to tax-approved pension schemes will be extended to include those
in other EU member states.
It will, however, be necessary for the foreign insurance company to appoint
a fiscal representative in the UK (or enter into other arrangements) to
secure compliance with the company's tax obligations.
</TEXT>
<XX>
