<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Government Statements): Plan to amend tax
treatment of repo deals - Gilts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Changes to the tax treatment of approved stock lending arrangements and sale
and repurchase transactions (repos) are planned. The changes will take
effect from Royal assent.
Where collateral for approved stock lending arrangements is provided in the
form of cash, and the lender receives interest on the cash collateral
without deduction of tax and passes it on in full to the borrower, the
borrower will get relief for the interest paid and will be able to pay it
without deduction of tax.
Anomalies in the application of existing legislation to repos will also be
addressed.
Stock lending is an important mechanism for supporting the liquidity of the
securities and equity markets. It enables stock to be borrowed to meet an
obligation to sell to a third party. The disposals and acquisitions that
arise are ignored for tax purposes if the stock lending arrangements are
approved.
Removal of the anomalies in the application of existing legislation to repos
will ensure that double charges and double reliefs do not arise. The
chancellor's intention is to enable those lenders who prefer cash as
collateral to take a more active part in the market.
The Bank of England yesterday published a consultative document on
establishing an open market in the sale and repurchase of government
securities.
The Inland Revenue will be consulting shortly on the potential tax
implications of a gilt repo market. The consultation period will end on
January 31 1995.
Marketmakers in gilts can already borrow stock using the services of the
stock exchange money brokers in what are in effect bilateral repo
transactions. An open repo market will allow all market participants to use
repos.
The introduction of an open repo market would mark an important further
development of the structure of the gilts market. Repos should improve
liquidity and efficiency, reducing yields and the government's debt interest
costs.
Each reduction in yields of just one basis point - one-hundredth of 1 per
cent - will save more than Pounds 25m a year of public expenditure.
</TEXT>
<XX>
