<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Government Statements): Package aims to get the
unemployed back to work - Incentives for employers and aid for former
claimants
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Under a banner of new work incentives and a budget for work, the chancellor
announced a Pounds 680m package of measures to help the unemployed back to
work and reduce the cost to employers of taking them on.
There are four measures to encourage employers to take on people who have
been out of work, particularly for long spells:
Employer national insurance contributions cut by 0.6 per cent from April
1995, for all employees earning less than Pounds 205 a week, at a cost to
the Treasury of Pounds 250m a year.
Employer NIC holiday: from April 1996, employers who take on someone who has
been out of work for at least two years will be able to get a full NIC
rebate for that person for up to one year. On average, employers will save
more than Pounds 300 for every person they take on, at a cost of Pounds 45m
a year.
Expansion of Work Trials scheme: there will be more opportunities for
employers who give people who have been unemployed for more than six months
a three-week trial in a job before deciding whether to take them on
permanently. Unemployed people will continue to receive their benefits
during the trial, so the scheme is free to employers. There will be 150,000
Work Trial places over the next three years, costing Pounds 30m.
* New Workstart pilot schemes: there will be more grants for employers who
take on the long-term unemployed, through further Workstart pilots. Details
of the pilots are to be finalised, but around 5,000 people will benefit at a
total cost of Pounds 8m.
In addition, the Chancellor announced four measures to ease the transition
from unemployment to work:
Speeding up housing benefit and council tax benefit, plus four-week rent and
council tax guarantee for people taking jobs. From April 1996 people who
have been out of work for at least six months will be able to get their
housing benefit and council tax benefit paid at full existing rates for the
first four weeks after they take a job. The aim will also be to ensure
people are told how much continuing help they will get with housing and
council tax benefit within the four weeks, and that this will be paid
promptly. The scheme will cost Pounds 50m a year and 440,000 people will
benefit. The government will shortly be consulting local authorities who are
responsible for paying housing benefit and council tax benefit.
Speeding up the payment of family credit The government plans that by April
1996, 95 per cent of family credit claims from employees will be dealt with
within five working days of the claim being received by the Department of
Social Security. The cost is Pounds 5m a year and 400,000 people will
benefit.
announced in October, will be tax free. People who lose benefit because they
do a few hours work while claiming income support or the new Jobseeker's
Allowance will get a cash lump sum of up to Pounds 1,000 when they move to
work of at least 16 hours.
National extension of Jobfinder's Grant: Up to 25,000 grants will be
available to people who have been unemployed for at least two years when
they start a lower-paid job, to help with initial work expenses. The grants
are worth an average Pounds 200 each and will cost Pounds 5m a year.
Two measures to help people who want full-time work:
Extra money for family credit claimants working full-time: anyone who is
entitled to family credit who takes a full-time job (at least 30 hours a
week) will get an extra Pounds 10 a week, from July 1995, at a cost of
Pounds 205m a year. People who also receive housing benefit and council tax
benefit will be able to keep an extra Pounds 10 of income before these
benefits are affected, guaranteeing that they will benefit by the full
amount of the extra family credit. Some 350,000 families on low incomes will
be helped.
Further Jobmatch pilot schemes: people who have been unable to find a
full-time job will be helped to build up full-time hours and wages by taking
on a number of part-time jobs. The design of the new pilots is being
finalised, but there will be up to 3,000 opportunities at an annual cost of
Pounds 5m.
For the unemployed, there were three measures to keep unemployed people in
touch with the labour market:
National extension of 1-2-1 interviews and Workwise courses: help for 18 to
24s unemployed for a year to look for work more effectively
Community Action: work experience and help in looking for work for long-term
unemployed.
The measures also included a Pounds 25m pilot scheme for unemployed people
without children. The pilot scheme will run for three years from October
1996, and include 20,000 people or one in 25 childless people in the UK. If
they show the scheme is successful, the government will consider introducing
the benefit nationally. Consultations on the details of the scheme will
begin in April 1995.
Mr Michael Portillo, the employment secretary, welcomed the budget measures
and said: 'Prospects look good. Unemployment is down by 455,000 from the
December 1992 peak and by a third of a million compared with a year ago. We
have more of our working-age population in jobs than any of our major
European partners. Our Employment Service is meeting and beating its
toughest ever targets to place unemployed people into jobs. And the new
Jobseeker's Allowance will ensure that our benefit system is simplified and
more than ever geared to helping every individual who wants work.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
