<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Government Statements): Amendments in wake of
changes in accounting - Profit-related pay
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The rules governing profit-related pay schemes are to change with the aim of
ensuring that, after a recent change in accounting practice, tax relief for
PRP can continue to be linked as closely as possible to profits which
genuinely reflect the efforts of the employees in the scheme.
Under the proposed changes, the following could be taken into account or
left out of account in drawing up profit and loss accounts for PRP purposes:
profits or losses on the sale or termination of an operation;
costs of a fundamental restructuring having a material effect on operations;
profits or losses on the disposal of fixed assets;
the tax effects of any of these items.
The proposed changes will replace the current treatment of 'extraordinary
items' for PRP purposes. This will apply to profit and loss accounts for
profit periods beginning on or after the date of Royal assent to the finance
bill.
The PRP legislation provides that 'extraordinary items' may be left out of
account, or taken into account, in drawing up profit and loss accounts for
registered PRP schemes, notwithstanding the accounting requirements imposed
by the Companies Acts.
At the time the legislation was introduced, 'extraordinary items' were
defined, in Statement of Standard Accounting Practice 6 (SSAP 6), to include
a range of items which could not be said to reflect the efforts of the
workforce.
The recent replacement of SSAP 6 by Financial Reporting Standard 3 (FRS 3)
has altered the definition of 'extraordinary items'. Many items which might
previously have been treated as 'extraordinary' for accountancy purposes may
no longer be so treated.
That change makes it more difficult for businesses to draw up PRP schemes
under which PRP is closely linked to profits which genuinely reflect
employees' efforts.
The Inland Revenue announced in July that this change would require an
amendment to the tax legislation.
The chancellor proposes to replace the reference to 'extraordinary items' in
the PRP legislation with a reference to the following three categories of
'exceptional items', which FRS 3 requires to be shown separately on the face
of the profit and loss account after operating profit:
profits or losses on the sale or termination of an operation;
costs of a fundamental restructuring having a material effect on operations;
profits or losses on the disposal of fixed assets.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P8721 Accounting, Auditing, and Bookkeeping Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
