<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Comment): Give and take - John Plender looks in
vain for fiscal logic and finds politics instead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PLENDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This was clearly in-tended to be a pro-business Budget. But is that what
Kenneth Clarke actually delivered? The answer would be yes, if fiscal
handouts were all that mattered: somewhat bizarrely, the biggest single item
of tax relief in the whole package was the Pounds 605m of transitional
relief to cope with the impact of the first five-yearly review of valuations
for business rates. Yet while such largesse will no doubt be welcomed by the
business community, there remains a problem. As with Mr Clarke's first
Budget, it is remarkably difficult to find any coherent pattern in the
welter of business taxation measures that the chancellor expects to promote
a strong and thriving economy.
Mr Clarke's rhetoric puts all the emphasis on manufacturing and small
business. Many of the Budget measures do indeed point in their direction.
Exporters can expect a 10 per cent reduction in premiums from the Export
Credits Guarantee Department, along with increased cover for some developing
markets. The growth of the venture capital sector will be enhanced by
changes to the enterprise investment scheme introduced last year.
Fine tuning of the loan guarantee scheme and changes in insolvency
legislation, to be undertaken jointly with the Department of Trade and
Industry, are worthwhile, if worthy, structural changes. The reduction in
the administrative burden in relation to VAT and PAYE will, meantime, be
widely welcomed in the small business community.
The broad thrust of Mr Clarke's rhetoric is further underlined by the
contrast between what he is prepared to do for small business and what he is
happy to take from the upper echelons of the financial services sector.
Private investors in Venture Capital Trusts will benefit from income tax
relief at 20 per cent, capital gains tax reinvestment relief on new shares
of up to Pounds 100,000 a year, and exemption from tax for all income and
gains on the investments concerned. This is an undeniably generous break for
investment in unquoted companies.
Sophisticated investors in deep discount bonds and index-related securities
are, on the other hand, singled out for anti-avoidance measures. Tough, in
fact, on City folk. This is a far cry from the Thatcher era, when Mr
Clarke's predecessors rejoiced in the job-creating potential of a financial
services sector that today accounts for 18 per cent of GDP.
Yet at second glance Mr Clarke's stated bias is less pronounced than it
appears. The beer, wine and spirits industry, hardly at the small end of the
enterprise spectrum and well looked after over the years by Tory
chancellors, has escaped any increase in duty. Note, too, that reliefs from
capital gains on investment in unquoted companies are now to be extended to
another heavily cosseted group, the farmers. Also to property investors and
developers - though the property industry will complain it is also the
victim of anti-avoidance measures.
On the central issues of corporation tax Mr Clarke's instincts appear to be
fairly consistent. He has once again resisted the demands of industrialists
for an increase in the capital allowances for investment in plant and
machinery. The industrialists' argument was that an increase in the present
25 per cent allowance would encourage investment by lowering corporation tax
bills and reducing the cost of capital. Yet there is academic evidence to
support Mr Clarke's judgment, which suggests that the impact of such
tinkering would be modest. The chancellor has also decided against following
his predecessor in reducing the rate of advance corporation tax and the
associated tax credit - a pro-business measure in that companies will not
find themselves confronting higher funding costs for pension schemes because
of a reduction in pension fund dividend income.
This brings us to the central question. The chancellor boasted of the
government's record in improving competitiveness and sharpening incentives
through the development of the tax system. Yet the chief way of fulfilling
those objectives, apart from establishing a sound macro-economic policy
stance, is to ensure the overall taxation of savings and investment offers
investors and businessmen the right sticks and carrots. This the present
system signally fails to do.
The corporation tax system is not neutral as between debt financed and
equity financed investment. Investors pay corporation tax on some profits,
but not on others; they sometimes pay income tax on dividends, sometimes
not. In effect, the imputation system of tax introduced in 1973 encourages
high dividend distributions in a world where tax exempt investors like
pension funds constitute the majority of equity shareholders. There is also
a growing debate as to the potential constraints that this implies for
investment in plant and machinery given the increasing evidence that
internal finance is not a perfect substitute for external finance for
corporate investment.
The related policy issues, which were to be explored by Mr Stephen Dorrell
before his move from the Treasury to the heritage ministry, were driven off
the chancellor's agenda by the intervention of Lord Hanson, who argued that
a Tory government was being seduced by Labour-style policies.
Here, then, is the most important dog that failed to bark in the Budget
speech. All we have, instead, is a few marginal changes to Peps, Tessas and
personal pension arrangements on the savings front, and the basic assertion
that low corporation tax rates for the successful are better than high
capital allowances for all.
That is not to say that the Budget is without logic. Simply that the logic
is political rather than fiscal. Mr Clarke has no aspiration towards the
wider reforms that would be needed to deliver the robust business enterprise
he claims to want.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
