<PROFILE>_AN-EK3EKAFFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Comment): Just short of paradise - The financial
markets hoped for even more
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For all his repeated claims that his various pint-sized proposals were
'important' and 'substantial' Kenneth Clarke's second Budget lived fully up
to its billing as the boring one in between last year's tough book-balancer
and next year's would-be vote-grabber.
The only really interesting aspect, perhaps, will be whether the harshest of
the pre-ordained tax increases - notably the second dollop of value added
tax on domestic fuel - will actually get through a troublesome House of
Commons. As a shrewd politician Mr Clarke took a good deal of trouble to
soothe Tory MPs' consciences by tossing extra pensioner handouts.
The dullness will not be regretted by the financial markets, however. They
were relying on the government not to do anything rash, and it has not,
although the officially forecast numbers for spending and borrowing over the
next two years are not quite up to the best expectations.
For example, despite the accelerating economic boom the Treasury has only
revised its estimate of the current year's public sector borrowing
requirement down from the Pounds 36.1bn indicated in June to Pounds 34.5bn,
when some City scribblers have had their eyes on a PSBR near Pounds 30bn.
However, the vision of a PSBR as low as Pounds 5bn by 1997-98 is being
dangled before a tantalised gilt-edged market. That prospective near-balance
could provide the framework for a final pre-election Budget in November
1996, always supposing that the beleaguered government can last that long.
The risk for the bond market is that the appeal of this return to financial
prudence will be lost in another boom-and-bust exercise, as taxes are cut
merrily in the next two Budgets and the economy is allowed to overheat. The
Treasury has growth slowing to 3 1/4 per cent next year - highly convenient,
but several City economists have recently been raising their growth
projections.
Political uncertainties are important for gilts, but no more so than for
bond markets in other countries such as France or the US, let alone Italy.
As the figures stand, UK government bonds are looking better-placed than
those of most other countries. Only the UK's inflationary history is
preventing this from being demonstrated in yields.
One way for the government to cash in on the improved outlook and reduce its
borrowing costs would be for the Bank of England to find ways of making the
gilt-edged market more user-friendly for foreigners. The 'not invented here'
approach has long dominated the stuffy UK government bond market. Auctions
have been introduced; but the long list of stocks is regarded as confusing,
liquidity is sometimes inadequate because of the absence of an open sale and
repurchase ('repo') market, and there are difficulties over quixotic
withholding taxes applying to some issues and some foreign investors.
It is evident from the Bank of England's consultative paper that the
authorities are desperate to reconcile the possibly irreconcileable. On the
one hand, a repo market would attract speculative traders, increasing
liquidity but arguably not raising volatility. Yet it is 'of great
importance that gilt repo activity should take place within a
properly-regulated framework'.
Improving the mechanics of the market might help to reduce borrowing costs.
The chancellor made the observation that each basis point of yield saved -
each hundredth of a percentage point - would result in an economy worth
Pounds 25m a year. The question is whether those savings might have to be
paid for in some other way. It is difficult to imagine that an effective
repo market could be introduced without allowing gross dividends to be paid
on all issues. An attempt to restrict this tax exemption to foreigners only
would create discontinuities and threaten, for instance, to encourage a huge
trade in buying and selling coupons.
If the gilt-edged market is to be truly internationalised it will have to be
on the basis of interest paid gross. That would no doubt involve some loss
of domestic tax revenue, through deferment and, worse, evasion, creating a
big loophole to offset the closing of some tiny ones in the Budget. The tax
issue will be covered in a forthcoming Inland Revenue paper, the
separateness of which suggests that the authorities have not yet grasped the
point.
Tax inconsistencies are apparent on the domestic scene, too. For some reason
the Inland Revenue is opening up tax-exempt personal equity plans to
corporate bonds but not, it seems, to gilts. It is not clear why the
government should be discriminating against its own paper.
Is it not, anyway, a bit late to be worrying about foreign investment in
gilts? True, it may have been disappointing for the Bank of England to see
foreigners turn net sellers this year, leading to some sticky moments in the
auctions.
But net gilt issuance, some Pounds 48bn in 1993-94, is tumbling, and may be
less than Pounds 20bn next year. With the balance of payments approaching
actual balance there is no underlying need for external finance. Moreover UK
pension funds are likely to become much more active buyers of gilts because
of the introduction of a minimum solvency standard under the forthcoming
Pensions Bill. By 1997-98, if you believe the numbers, they will only be
able to buy gilts through the secondary market, so that foreigners will be
selling, while yield spreads will be shrinking and reversing.
Some might say that priority should have been given to the requirements of
UK pension funds. The Goode Committee on pension law reform asked for
special securities to match pension fund liabilities. But the authorities
are neglecting their biggest potential domestic long-term investors in
favour of solicitation of peripatetic foreigners.
Can you believe it all? The government is promising a further squeeze on
public sector pay and employment levels, which may be difficult to deliver.
It seems to have slipped at the first hurdle of PSBR expectations for
1994-95. We are entering the politically more dangerous phase of this
parliament. But we should put it all into perspective. To an Italian or
Swedish investor the UK might look like an unattainable financial paradise.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MKTS  Market data.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
