<DOCNO>FT944-6236</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EK3EKAE9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (What It Means For You): Advance payment of fuel
bills advised - Benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER and MARTIN MACCONNOL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumers are advised to pay fuel bills in advance, in spite of the measures
introduced to offset April's rise in value added tax on domestic heating
from 8 per cent to 17.5 per cent.
The main beneficiaries of the measures appear to be pensioners, although
they will also help people receiving benefit. Mr Kenneth Clarke,
compromising after recent calls for the waiving of the second phase of the
VAT increase, said the benefits would offset the tax for many people.
The government has set aside Pounds 10m for home insulation grants and
increased the cold-weather payment - the benefit payable after seven
successive days of zero temperatures - from Pounds 6 to Pounds 8.50 a week.
From next year retirement pensions will rise to help offset VAT on fuel.
Single pensioners will get an extra Pounds 52 and couples Pounds 73. The
element to offset VAT will rise to Pounds 68 and Pounds 96 respectively from
1996.
Tax experts say consumers should still try to pay as much as possible of
future fuel bills by March 31, before the 9.5 per cent rise comes into
effect.
The chancellor said that Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary,
would today announce changes in the benefits system designed to boost the
public purse.
Local authorities will be capped on the level of housing benefit they can
pay tenants renting from private landlords. Authorities will not be fully
reimbursed for benefit significantly above the average for the area and type
of property.
Mr Lilley will also announce more limits on income support for mortgages.
Support will not be available for the first nine months on most mortgages
taken out after October 1995. New mortgage holders of working age will be
expected to insure mortgage interest payments against periods of sickness
and unemployment.
The Budget also made provisions to encourage the long-term unemployed back
to work - and to encourage employers to take them on.
From April 1996 employers will have a National Insurance contributions
holiday, while the jobseekers will gain by the speeding of the payment of
family credit to those moving into employment. The back-to-work bonus,
announced by Mr Lilley in October, will be exempt from income tax.
</TEXT>
