<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (What It Means For You): Reforms to tax-paying
pushed to the forefront - Self-assessment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Self-assessment, the biggest shake-up in the UK tax system since PAYE was
introduced half a century ago, crept ever closer yesterday with the Budget
announcement of a raft of anti-avoidance measures.
The chancellor found time in his speech to tell the House of the 'positive
response' so far to the reforms put forward by the Inland Revenue and he
promised to try to keep the burdens on employers to a minimum.
The reforms were set in train in 1993 and the progress towards
implementation is now accelerating. Eight million taxpayers will have to
take part when self-assessment comes on stream in the 1996-97 tax year. For
the newly self-employed, compliance began on April 5 this year.
'SA', as it is known, catches more than taxpayers. If you are an employer
the system will require you to provide employees with more information than
in the past. Details on what employers would have to provide were published
yesterday.
While the Revenue points out that the new system will ultimately be cheaper,
faster, simpler, and more accurate, taxpayers face changes on a big scale.
SA is a new tax system, with a new set of tax forms, and a new set of
payment dates.
Of those who currently return a tax form, and who will be caught by the new
legislation, half are self-employed and half employees. They include
business partners, directors, and employees and pensioners with complicated
tax affairs.
SA has several basic building blocks but is essentially founded on the
assessment of tax with respect to figures provided by the taxpayer. The
taxpayer is invited to carry out this assessment themselves on the forms
provided - but this is not compulsory. Everything else is.
The new system is one based on current year assessment. Your tax bill for
any year relates to your income in that same year. The new system brings
together all income, and capital gains, to be taxed at one time. The present
system has different payment dates, for different years, and different types
of income.
The new system has a set of payment dates which are fixed. Three payments
are made in a year. Two are due on January 31 in one single transaction:
they are the first payment on account for the current year and a payment, or
refund claim, to settle up on the previous year. The second payment on
account will be due on July 31.
For example a taxpayer with income tax liability of Pounds 5,200 for
1997-98, the first year of current year assessment, would pay Pounds 2,600
on January 31 1999 and Pounds 2,600 on July 31 1999. If the actual tax
liability for 1998-99 is found to be Pounds 5,600 then on January 31 2000
the taxpayer would pay Pounds 400, the balance for the previous year, and
Pounds 2,800. On July 31 the taxpayer would pay the second instalment of
Pounds 2,800. And so on.
The new tax form itself will have to be in by January 31 after the end of
the tax year it covers in those cases where the taxpayer has
'self-assessed': in other words calculated their own tax. If the taxpayer
has opted for 'revenue calculation' the return, with all the relevant
information, must be in by the previous September 30.
The system is based on 'process now, check later' in that, apart from
obvious errors, the taxpayer's figures are accepted. However all returns
will be checked and a sample reviewed and taxpayers interviewed. Such
inquiries will usually have to begin within 12 months of the due date for
the return. There is also a system of penalties.
Yesterday the chancellor announced measures to stop tax avoidance which
could come about by the moving of profits or income into the transitional
period between accounts compiled on the preceding year basis and those on
current year basis.
Because of the overlap between the periods, an averaging out of profits is
proposed and some profits will drop out of the reckoning entirely in order
to make sure there is no double taxation. The scope for manipulation is wide
and the Treasury signalled its intention to act in March this year. The
measures announced yesterday are now open for consultation.
While agents, such as accountants and other tax practitioners, are already
preparing themselves for the transition period and beyond, many individual
taxpayers may be in for a surprise. The new tax form not only looks
different but it asks different questions.
At present self-employed taxpayers who file returns can write 'as per
accounts' on their returns and post them off with the accounts attached. The
new form will require the figures to be placed in a pre-set format.
PAYE taxpayers who also file a tax return can, at present, cut corners by
referring to employer-provided documents in answer to questions, for
example, on benefits in kind. Employees will now need this information from
their employers - and they will need it in time to avoid penalty.
</TEXT>
