<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (What It Means For You): Personal bands to be
unfrozen - Income tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Personal allowances are to be unfrozen for the first time in two years and
age-related allowances are to be increased above the rate of inflation,
Scheherazade Daneshkhu writes.
Restrictions announced previously will still apply, however. These measures
will take place from April 6 1995:
Personal allowances will be indexed. The single person's allowance will
therefore rise from Pounds 3,445 to Pounds 3,525.
Age-related allowances will increase above the rate of inflation. The
personal allowance for those aged 65-74 will rise from Pounds 4,200 to
Pounds 4,630, those aged 75 and over will see a rise from Pounds 4,370 to
Pounds 4,800.
The married couple's age allowance will rise for those aged 65 to 74 from
Pounds 2,665 to Pounds 2,995. It will increase for those aged 75 and over
from Pounds 2,705 to Pounds 3,035. These measures were announced in the last
Budget.
The income limit for age-related allowances will increase from Pounds 14,200
to Pounds 14,600.
The lower-rate income tax band of 20 per cent will be extended from the
first Pounds 3,000 of income to Pounds 3,200 - a tax saving of just Pounds
10 a year. The threshold for higher-rate taxpayers will ris from Pounds
23,700 to Pounds 24,300. The rates of income tax are unchanged.
On CGT and IHT the annual capital gains tax exemption is to increase from
its current Pounds 5,800 to Pounds 6,000 and the threshold for inheritance
tax moves up from Pounds 150,000 to Pounds 154,000.
Increases in restricted allowances will not, however, compensate for income
tax increases which were announced in the November 1993 Budget.
Relief on the married couple's allowance will be restricted to 15 per cent
of Pounds 1,720 from the current 20 per cent, so its tax value will fall
from Pounds 344 to Pounds 258. This restriction affects the widow's
bereavement allowance and the additional allowance in respect of children.
Mortgage interest tax relief will be restricted from 20 per cent to 15 per
cent.
Individuals making maintenance payments receive a deduction from their
income of Pounds 1,720. In the current year relief is given at 20 per cent
but from April 6 1995, it will be restricted to 15 per cent.
</TEXT>
