<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (What It Means For You): Unquoted companies 'more
attractive' - High-risk investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investing in unquoted companies will be a much more attractive proposition
in future with the broadening of tax incentives on two schemes: Enterprise
Investment Schemes and Venture Capital Trusts. In some cases, tax relief of
up to 60 per cent will be available.
With both schemes, the chancellor has made use of an extension of the
reinvestment relief for investing in unquoted companies, which was
introduced in last year's Budget. This relief allows a capital gains tax
liability from any investment to be deferred indefinitely if the gain is
invested in an unquoted trading company meeting certain conditions.
Rules on which companies qualify as unquoted trading companies under the
scheme were also relaxed in yesterday's Budget. The main restriction to be
abolished was the 'interest in land' rule, which disqualified a company if
more than half its assets were in land and buildings at any point during the
three years after investment. Relief has also been extended to property
development and farming companies.
Enterprise Investment Schemes were introduced last year as a successor to
the much-exploited Business Expansion Scheme, to encourage direct investment
in small unquoted trading companies. They carry a basic incentive of 20 per
cent up-front income tax relief on investments up to Pounds 100,000 a year,
if shares in the company are held for at least five years.
Now the chancellor has added the possibility of combining the income tax
relief with rollover reinvestment relief for capital gains, giving a
potential total tax relief of 60 per cent for higher-rate taxpayers who have
gains to reinvest.
The reinvestment relief applies to assets disposed of on or after yesterday.
It can be used if the disposal of assets is made up to one year before or
three years after the subscription for shares under the EIS is made.
Venture capital trusts: plans to introduce a new kind of venture capital
trust were announced in the 1993 Budget, with further details given in a
consultative document published earlier this year. The trusts will take the
form of quoted investment funds, intended to provide ordinary investors with
an easy way to invest in a portfolio of very small, growing unquoted
companies.
The original proposals gave investments in the new trusts tax treatment in
line with personal equity plans: tax-free income and capital gains, but no
up-front incentives.
Yesterday, however, the chancellor said that investments in the trusts would
attract both 20 per cent income tax relief and capital gains tax
reinvestment relief, adding up to a possible total of 60 per cent tax
relief, as with enterprise investment schemes. Investors can put up to
Pounds 100,000 a year into the trusts. Again, the reliefs only apply if the
shares are held for at least five years.
The chancellor also announced details of what restrictions there would be on
the type of investment the new trusts made. Investments can include both
equity and loans (with a minimum term of five years), but at least half the
investments must be in new ordinary shares.
At least 70 per cent of their investments must be in unquoted trading
companies, with no more than 15 per cent in any one company or group of
companies. To qualify as unquoted trading companies for this purpose,
companies must have assets of less than Pounds 10m before the investment is
made.
Venture capital trusts are due to be introduced from April next year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
