<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Their Budget): The pensioner
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Bill Caswell, 66: Former export consultant and, latterly, probation officer.
Lives with a friend in a large house on the Isle of Wight, and is divorced
with two grown-up children. He has no mortgage, a small pension of Pounds
6,500 but investments producing income of Pounds 30,000.
Said yesterday: 'For a retired person like me on a reasonable income there
were no nasty surprises. The VAT increases on fuel do not really affect me,
since I anticipated them by putting in a condensing boiler. Lower inflation
does not help everybody since higher inflation wipes out debt. But I am not
complaining.
The one thing I would like to have seen was tax benefits for the disabled. I
have become disabled recently and I do need help. I am little disappointed
about the increase in fuel taxes. If you live in the country like I do,
where public transport has collapsed, this is an extra burden. On the whole,
though, there was little to worry me.'
</TEXT>
