<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Public Spending): Ministry emerges virtually
unscathed - Defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Ministry of Defence emerged almost unscathed from this year's public
expenditure round, having suffered heavy losses in last year's Budget.
Cuts of the order of Pounds 250m over each of the next three years are
planned because inflation has proved lower than expected, but no large
equipment programmes are threatened by yesterday's announcement.
However, plans to privatise the MoD's housing stock were still left in
doubt.
Buoyed by a painless spending round, the MoD announced new equipment orders
for frigates and missiles for the RAF.
Invitations to tender for a final batch of up to three more Type 23
anti-submarine frigates will be issued.
Favourite to win the Pounds 450m frigate order is the Yarrow shipyard on the
Clyde owned by GEC, which is currently vying with British Aerospace for
control of the submarine maker VSEL.
Yarrow has built nine of the 13 Type 23 ships so far ordered.
Two new missiles were also confirmed for the RAF. A long-range conventional
attack missile will be ordered in 1996 at a cost of about Pounds 750m.
This will allow Tornados, Harriers and Eurofighters to attack targets up to
250km away with high accuracy.
The idea for the missile came from the Gulf war where US forces used
advanced munitions to great effect with their fighters able to stand off at
safe distances.
There are several possible competitors for the contract. Leading contenders
are the French company Matra with its Apache missile, McDonnell Douglas of
the US with its GrandSLAM and the UK team of GEC and BAe offering the
Pegasus missile.
The other missile for the RAF is a Pounds 700m anti-tank weapon primarily
intended to be launched from the Tornado and the Harrier.
It is intended to knock out tanks and armoured personnel carriers in
combination with the anti-tank helicopters the army is currently
considering.
GEC is offering its version of the US Hellfire missile while British
Aerospace is offering an adaptation of its Asraam anti-aircraft missile for
the competition.
The one issue which remained unresolved for the MoD in the Budget was the
gap in its funding for next year which would be caused by its failure to
sell its housing stock.
The ministry is relying on getting up to Pounds 500m for house sales in
1995-96 but has run into technical difficulties.
Yesterday it was still confident that the money would be raised in time.
</TEXT>
