<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Public Spending): Spending stays level in real
terms at Pounds 1.28bn - Science
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Science spending will remain exactly level in real terms at Pounds 1.282bn
next year.
'This is a good settlement,' said Mr David Hunt, the minister responsible
for science. 'After looking very carefully at all its expenditure
programmes, the government has again made science one of its priorities.'
Mr Robert Hughes, the junior science minister, added that the level outcome
was better than it looked at first sight, as the current year's science
budget was worth about 2 per cent more than in 1993-94 because of lower than
expected inflation - and Mr Hunt, unlike many of his colleagues had hung on
to the increase.
But Save British Science, a research lobby group, was disappointed. Mr John
Mulvey, SBS secretary, had expected a further rise of at least 2.5 per cent,
after a speech this year in which the prime minister said he expected
'spending on the science base to rise in real terms next year'.
'At a time when our economy is growing at 3.5 per cent a year, we can afford
to invest in the long-term future by spending more on research,' Mr Mulvey
said last night. 'This is a government with shorter term concerns.'
The government's science budget covers money spent directly by the Office of
Science and Technology through its five research councils - mainly on
university research. OST officials expected overall public spending on
research and development to decline again next year, because of cuts in
support for science and technology by the Ministry of Defence and Department
of Trade and Industry. But figures for all R&amp;D expenditure in 1995-96 will
not be available until next year.
