<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Public Spending): Gowrie applauds Pounds 5.1m
funds rise - Arts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The arts have done rather well out of the Budget. The grant for the Arts
Council of England in 1995-96 has been raised by Pounds 5.1m to Pounds
191.5m. A year ago, the council had its grant cut for the first time, by
Pounds 3.2m, and had been told to expect stand-still funding for next year.
But the new heritage secretary, Mr Stephen Dorrell, who has been criticised
for apparent indifference to his department, surprised the arts world
yesterday and won the plaudits of Lord Gowrie, chairman of the Arts Council.
'While the restitution still falls short in real terms, the secretary of
state has made an excellent start and the additional Pounds 5.1m will enable
arts organisations to trade their way out of recession,' he said.
The council will decide next month how to distribute its grant among its
clients, but the unexpected uplift should prevent the collapse of any
important arts companies, many of which have deficits.
The arts will also benefit from the extra Pounds 750,000 allocated to the
Business Sponsorship Incentive Scheme, bringing it up to Pounds 5.6m a year.
There was also good news in the chancellor's announcement that the
Foundation for Sport and the Arts would continue for at least the next five
years.
In total, Mr Dorrell managed to raise the budget of the Department of
National Heritage from Pounds 976m to Pounds 1.01bn, an increase roughly in
line with inflation.
Mr Dorrell has shown great interest in the potential of tourism to increase
the revenues of arts companies. From his budget he has allocated an extra
Pounds 2m to the British Tourist Authority over the next two years so it can
launch a new tourist marketing initiative for London.
</TEXT>
