<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Public Spending): Grant reduction draws criticism
 -Housing associations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plans to cut the amount of grant provided to housing associations were
strongly criticised last night by housing organisations which said it would
mean more homeless people.
Housing investment plans for England for 1994-5, including the rough
sleepers' allowance, have been cut from Pounds 1.73bn to Pounds 1.36bn; a
reduction of more than Pounds 300m.
The National Federation of Housing Associations said that would mean new
rented homes provided by associations would fall to only 10,000, against
this year's 25,000. That was in addition to a reduction of 9,000 homes
already announced, following a previous cut of Pounds 250m in the 1994-5
budget.
The federation said homes started for low-cost and shared ownership schemes
would fall from 20,000 to 12,500 next year. Reduced building programmes
could cost 4,000 construction jobs in 1994-5 and 7,900 the following year.
Higher benefit payments and lost tax revenue would cost the Exchequer Pounds
35m next year and Pounds 70m the year after, it added.
The Chartered Institute of Housing said the budget cuts would make it more
difficult for people on modest wages to find rented accommodation.
Mr Jim Coulter, chief executive of the National Federation of Housing
Associations, said: 'For three years the government has achieved falling
homeless figures, but Mr Clarke's announcement could mean that the level may
start to rise again.'
Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, said that falling construction costs
and increased private sector investment in association schemes had meant
that building programmes had been maintained.
From April, the government expects private investors to provide 42 per cent
of associations' finance, against 25 per cent private investment in 1989-90.
</TEXT>
