<PROFILE>_AN-EK3EKAEIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Tax): Landfill tax set for 1996 - Environment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A tax on landfill was the most obviously 'green' proposal in the Budget. But
the government will proceed cautiously before implementing a measure which
could be unpopular with industry.
Mr Clarke said that the tax would be introduced in 1996 and would raise
several hundred million pounds a year.
The tax would be collected by Customs and Excise, which means it would be
added, like value added tax, to the cost of waste disposal.
But to sweeten the pill, Mr Clarke made clear that the cost would be offset
by other measures, such as a reduction in National Insurance contributions,
meaning that its overall effect on industry would be neutral.
Fuller details will be contained in a consultation document which will be
published shortly.
The tax would be levied on all waste going to landfill (licensed rubbish
dumps). The purpose would be to make rubbish more expensive and encourage
industry to minimise waste or recycle it. Mr Clarke said: 'In some cases,
taxes actually do some good, by helping markets work better and by
discouraging harmful or wasteful activ-ities.'
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, welcomed the proposal because it
would add to a string of measures by government to deal with the waste
problem.
He stressed that the proposed offset meant that it was 'not fiscal, only
environmental'.
It was also welcomed by environmentalists. Mr Charles Secrett, director of
Friends of the Earth, said this was 'the greenest Budget yet'. He
particularly welcomed the chancellor's statement that a switch in taxation
could discourage activities which damage the environment while helping cut
the cost of employment.
But industry was less enthusiastic. Mr John Cridland, environment director
at the CBI, said that businessmen would need 'a cast-iron guarantee that
this will not add to costs'.
However, he welcomed the fact that government planned a period of
consultation before going ahead with the measure.
The National Association of Waste Disposal Contractors also took a cautious
line. 'We are not convinced that this kind of measure will necessarily
produce the promised environmental benefits,' said a spokesman.
He pointed out that recent tightening of dumping regulations had already
added to landfill costs, and any tax would come on top of that. A tax could
also encourage illegal dumping.
The UK produces about 140m tonnes of controlled waste each year of which
about 100m tonnes goes into landfill. This is a higher proportion than most
countries because the UK has relatively large landfill capacity and low
landfill costs, ranging from Pounds 3 to Pounds 10 per tonne, depending on
type.
But landfill levies have been introduced in a growing number of countries
such as Australia, Austria, Belgium, Denmark, France and Germany.
The issues for the UK are whether waste should be taxed by volume or value,
and whether toxic wastes should be more highly taxed than other types.
The level of the tax will also have to be decided, though judging by the
chancellor's remarks it would be several pounds a tonne.
</TEXT>
