<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Tax): Motorists 'treated like wallets on wheels'
 -Driving costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Motorists were a prime target in the Budget with significant increases in
real terms in duty on petrol and diesel and with a further rise in vehicle
excise duty for cars.
The average price of a gallon of unleaded petrol will rise by about 11p to
Pounds 2.45.
The Automobile Association condemned the chancellor's decision to add 2.5p
to a litre of petrol and 3p to the price of a litre of diesel.
Mr Clarke said that he was sticking to the government's commitment of a year
ago to increase road fuel duties on average by at least 5 per cent in real
terms. The rise, which took effect last night, was 'an important part of the
government's strategy to return carbon dioxide emissions to their 1990 level
in the year 2000', Mr Clarke said.
However this was attacked last night by motoring organisations. 'Increasing
fuel duty by 5 per cent as an 'environmental incentive' is a sham, while the
chancellor continues to increase vehicle excise duty, which is an antiquated
tax on ownership that does nothing for the environment,' the AA said.
It estimated last night that the average motorist's costs would increase by
about Pounds 40 a year with petrol costs jumping by Pounds 35 a year and the
cost of the tax disc rising by Pounds 5 a year to Pounds 135.
'Yet again Britain's 20m motorists have been treated like wallets on wheels
. . . Drivers deserved a tax holiday after shouldering 1993's swingeing 24
per cent increase in fuel costs and 18 per cent increase in vehicle excise
duty, but we have been clobbered again.'
The chancellor also closed the differential between the duty on diesel and
unleaded petrol, by raising the duty on diesel by about 3p a litre.
The vehicle excise duty for trucks is being left unchanged, but the increase
in diesel fuel duty will hit the road haulage sector.
The Freight Transport Association estimated that this would increase
industry's costs by Pounds 250m-Pounds 300m a year.
The government is planning to reform the vehicle excise duty system by
introducing 'continuous licensing', which will tax possession rather than
use of a vehicle. A consultation paper is to be issued.
Motorists such as classic car owners, who did not pay vehicle excise duty
now because their cars were genuinely off the road, would not be
disadvantaged, he said.
Mr Clarke said the move was designed to combat evasion and to help fight
crime by enabling the police accurately to check the ownership of vehicles.
New powers are also to be proposed allowing vehicles parked on public roads
without a valid tax disc to be wheel-clamped.
Vehicle excise duty is expected to raise Pounds 3.7bn in 1994-95.
Separately the system of concessions and exemptions from vehicle excise duty
is to be simplified and modernised with the number of different
concessionary classes to be reduced from 132 to nine.
Around 75 per cent of those vehicles currently receiving special treatment
will pay no more duty, and emergency vehicles, disabled drivers and most
tractors will be unaffected. Rates on some categories such as recovery, road
construction and street cleansing and lighting vehicles could rise steeply
by more than Pounds 4,000, but increases in the first year will be limited
to no more than Pounds 1,000.
</TEXT>
