<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Tax): Cover for directors granted relief -
Insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Insurance bought by companies to protect directors and employees against the
cost of legal actions arising in the course of their work will no longer be
taxed as a benefit in kind, the Inland Revenue announced yesterday.
The proposals, which are expected to come into effect from April at an
annual cost of about Pounds 40m, are likely to be welcomed by many
companies.
The Association of Insurance and Risk Managers had lobbied for tax relief on
such directors' and officers' liability and professional indemnity insurance
policies. The association argued these policies were a necessary business
expense and, as litigation against company directors becomes more common,
were increasingly important.
The proposals would remove the charge to tax on employees when employers pay
for employees' liability insurance or meet work-related uninsured
liabilities. They would also give relief for employees' expenditure on
liability insurance and work-related uninsured liabilities.
Uninsured liabilities will only be allowed relief when they could have been
insured against.
</TEXT>
