<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Tax): Business gives broad welcome to
'deregulatory measures' - Industrial reaction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Industrial Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chancellor's pledge to deliver a 'strong and thriving business economy'
while keeping a tight reign on public spending was taken on trust by much of
British industry yesterday.
But while there was a broad welcome for his package of 'tax relief and
deregulatory measures', there was some grumbling over particulars. There was
disappointment, for instance, that Mr Clarke had refused to increase capital
allowances as a way of boosting investment further.
Mr Howard Davies, director general of the Confederation of British Industry,
said the Budget 'scored well' by keeping tight control of public spending
and borrowing and holding interest rates down as a basis for sustained
economic growth.
Mr Davies welcomed the chancellor's 'imaginative measures' for the long-term
unemployed, particularly the reductions in national insurance contributions,
and the extension of in-work benefits. Both measures are in line with CBI
recommendations.
At the Engineering Employers' Federation, which groups many companies hit by
the recession, director-general Mr Graham Mackenzie expressed delight with
the chancellor's plan to get people back to work through national insurance
'holidays' for employers taking on people from the unemployed register. In
an early detailed estimate of what it could mean for the shop floor, the EEF
estimates that on an average engineering salary of Pounds 17,000, the NI
'holiday' could allow an employer to invest approximately Pounds 1,700 a
year on retraining.
The EEF also said that the international competitive support which it had
been seeking had been met in part by the cut in export insurance premiums
and enhanced terms for export insurance for developing markets.
The usually more hawkish Institute of Directors welcomed the chancellor's
focus on the transition from unemployment to work. However, its head of
policy Dr Ann Robinson said Mr Clarke had not gone far enough in effecting a
much broader reduction in NI contribution rates and employment regulation.
'It's a missed opportunity. . . it's just bits of tinkering without getting
to the heart of the problem.'
Along with other organisations representing manufacturers, the Machine Tool
Technologies Association's positive response to several measures was
overshadowed by disappointment that a campaign for increased capital
allowances failed.
It said the chancellor had missed a valuable opportunity to take decisive
steps to tackle the UK's structurally low levels of manufacturing
investment. Elsewhere, it welcomed lower export insurance premiums, and
proposals for handling corporate insolvencies - although it pointed out that
these would have been more significant if they had been introduced in 1991.
The Chemicals Industries Association broadly welcomed the Budget's emphasis
on job creation and the control of public spending.
But it expressed concern about a proposed tax on waste disposal in landfills
and the likely increase in business rates in the north of England where many
of its members have manufacturing sites.
Mr Ronnie Hampel, ICI's chief executive said that the measures to help
industry were 'understandably limited'. He added that he was 'disappointed
the chancellor did not see scope to provide greater incentives for
productive investment'.
In the information technology sector, Mr Javaid Aziz, chief executive of the
UK subsidiary of International Business Machines, was encouraged by a budget
which he thought would stimulate investment: 'The government is firmly
committed to a trend reduction in its borrowing. This means that interest
rates will not rise as much as they might.' The motor industry was 'pleased'
that the chancellor was continuing to seek to maintain stability in the
economy with sustainable growth. Vauxhall said that it was a 'steady as she
goes budget', and it left its forecast for the UK new car market unchanged
for 1994 at 1.9m, an increase of 6.9 per cent, and 2m for 1995.
The computing services business expects to benefit from measures to help
small and medium-sized companies, while the introduction of electronics
methods to pay social security benefits at Post Office represents a Pounds
300m opportunity for the industry.
Reporting by Jimmy Burns, Alan Cane, Andrew Baxter, Daniel Green and Kevin
Done.
</TEXT>
