<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Tax): Big business gives its verdict
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Andrew Buxton
chairman, Barclays Bank
'It was a low-key but constructive Budget with plenty of encouragement for
small businesses and the unemployed.
It was clear that with the economy set fair he did not want to upset the
apple cart.
The transitional relief for business rates will be particularly welcome news
for small firms.
His PSBR predictions are in line with current CBI forecasts and if he can
get us in balance in three years' time then it will have been a great
achievement and may even allow for some tax-cutting measures at the end of
next year. All this is against the backdrop of a stable, low-inflation
environment.'
*****
Peter Jarvis
chief executive, Whitbread
'I am delighted the chancellor has held duty rates for a second year and has
recognised the cross-Channel problem.
However, he cannot rely on European action and will need to go further by
actually cutting rates unless he wants to see pubs closing all over the
country.'
Simon Ward, Whitbread's strategic affairs director, said: 'The cross-Channel
issue is not going to go away. It won't be easy to convince the French to
raise their duty rates. I don't see why they should hike their rates just to
please the UK government in what is a self-imposed problem. We would have
preferred the chancellor to reduce the rate of beer duty to that more in
line with current French levels - 5p a pint, compared with over 30p in the
UK.'
*****
Sir Brian Pearse
chairman, Lucas
'Companies such as ours have worked extremely hard through the recession to
improve global competitiveness.
We welcome this 'steady as she goes' Budget that should enable us to
continue this improvement in the UK and overseas.
However, we are disappointed with the apparent erosion of the differential
on duties on diesel and unleaded petrol because of the proven economic and
environmental advantages of diesel.
Overall, the Budget strengthens our quiet confidence in the future. We were
hoping the chancellor would not treat this year as one for dramatic changes.
We wanted minimum interference from the chancellor and that is what has
happened.'
*****
Sir Lawrie Barratt
chairman, Barratt Developments
'Unfortunately the chancellor has not announced any measures to stimulate
the UK housing market.
The market had been improving until September's half point interest rate
rise. This increase was totally unnecessary and I believe the chancellor
should have taken the opportunity to reverse this interest rate rise . . .
and restore housebuyers' confidence.
Furthermore, nothing was done for the 10m homeowners with mortgages who have
suffered so greatly in recent years as their mortgage tax relief has been
eroded. This erosion has had a damaging effect on the UK housing market.
All in all, I think the government should accept that a strong and stable
housing market is crucial to the recovery of the economy in general.'
*****
Ian Prosser
chairman, Bass
'There were no particular surprises in the Budget, although I was
disappointed that the chancellor did not reduce beer duty and that he felt
it necessary to impose gaming licence duty on amusement machines.
However, I am glad that he recognised the cross-Channel problem and that he
will address the issue with our European counterparts. I hope they will
listen.
Given the strength of the economy, I hope he will have the flexibility to
cut excise duty rates next year.
Overall, however, the chancellor's priorities were correct and I would agree
with his objective of sustaining strong UK economic growth through
investment and exports.'
*****
Sir Trevor Chinn
chairman, Lex Services
'The Budget message from the chancellor to industry was that the economy is
now heading in the right direction.
It was a 'steady as she goes' Budget and he is absolutely right to pursue a
low-inflation economy as the fruits of this will eventually feed through
into increased consumer expenditure.
This will obviously help industry and benefit businesses like our own.
His move to reduce VAT on leased cars seems to be favourable to our own
particular industry, although it is impossible to quantify its impact at
this stage.'
*****
David Simon
chief executive, BP Group
'This is a Budget which should please business. It is broadly
revenue-neutral and it proposes no changes that would jeopardise steady
recovery and the continuing squeeze on inflation.
It demonstrates that public expenditure is clearly under control and sound
fiscal and monetary policy is in place. Additional support for UK exporters
will help continued growth.
The strength of UK companies in export markets is a very encouraging feature
of current performance in the economy.
The chancellor's measures to promote the success of small companies and to
encourage recruitment of the long-term unemployed are also helpful.'
</TEXT>
