<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Tax): Incentives aim to boost private investment
 -Venture capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A new investment vehicle designed to encourage up to Pounds 2.5bn of private
investment in unquoted companies was greeted with enthusiasm by venture
capitalists as a measure that could substantially increase the flow of
capital to small companies.
The tax incentives attached to the Venture Capital Investment Trusts went
significantly further than most venture capitalists expected.
The chancellor did not, however, raise the maximum size of any single
investment that the Venture Capital Trust managers will be able to make
beyond the Pounds 1m level set in a consultative document published earlier
this year.
Investors will be able to claim 20 per cent up-front income tax relief on
the purchase of shares in the trusts. But they will also be able to roll
over capital gains realised through the sale of almost any other asset which
are then re-invested in the Venture Capital Trust (VCT) shares.
While this latter relief is in effect only a deferral of a capital gains tax
liability, the effect of the two incentives is to make up to 60 per cent of
any investment in the Venture Capital trust shares eligible for some form of
tax relief.
Investors will be limited to investments of Pounds 100,000 a year and the
trusts will not be able to invest in property companies.
Any capital gains or dividends made on the venture capital trust shares will
also be free of tax, giving the Venture Capital Trusts a status equivalent
to Personal Equity Plans.
Mr Michael Walton, managing director of Gartmore Venture Capital, said the
chancellor had 'really pushed the boat out' in an effort to attract
investors. The only constraint would be on finding investment opportunities.
Many venture capital houses that might consider launching venture capital
trusts will not have focused before on making investments as small as Pounds
1m and in companies with less than Pounds 10m in assets, as the trust rules
require.
Mr John Orpen, partner at accountants Coopers &amp; Lybrand, said the measures
would bring investment in private companies within the grasp of many
ordinary investors.
The chancellor also extended capital gains tax roll-over relief to the
Enterprise Scheme which replaced the Business Expansion Scheme last December
but which has attracted very little investor interest.
The chancellor is understood to be particularly enthusiastic about the
potential for Venture Capital Trusts to attract private equity into dynamic
smaller companies that do not have access to capital markets and may not
have enough security to raise bank debt. He believes these companies are
crucial in the drive to increase the pace of job creation.
</TEXT>
