<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (The Economy): Rapid fall in borrowing fuels tax
cut expectation - PSBR outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHANIE FLANDERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Budget announced a much more rapid reduction in the public sector
borrowing requirement than its predecessor, from Pounds 34.4bn this year to
only Pounds 5bn in three years' time.
Lower than expected inflation explains the bulk of the improvement in the
public sector finances. Mr Kenneth Clarke's first budget predicted a PSBR of
Pounds 38bn in 1994-5, falling to Pounds 12bn by 1997-8.
Most economists had expected Mr Clarke to announce a more rapid medium-term
reduction in the PSBR than he predicted a year ago. But the prediction of a
budget surplus will raise speculation that tax rates will be lowered in the
next few years.
The cumulative effect of the reduced cash spending totals announced
yesterday is that overall spending in 1997-98 will be Pounds 9bn lower than
predicted a year ago, at Pounds 272bn.
The Treasury's lower forecasts for future inflation will eventually mean
that tax receipts will be lower than previous forecast. By 1998, general
government receipts are expected to be Pounds 8.5bn below the level
predicted last year.
The overall effect of lower inflation, however, is positive, because of the
scope for lower cash spending totals. This year's fall in unemployment also
contributed, by reducing the cost of social security.
Yesterday's amended public spending plans provide for spending to rise at
less than 3 per cent in nominal terms over the next three years, or 0.25 per
cent annual real growth.
The faster reduction in the level of the PSBR means that the Treasury now
expects net public sector debt as a percentage of GDP to peak at 42.75 per
cent in 1996, falling to 36.75 per cent by the end of the century.
The Treasury pointed out that the new forecasts implied the UK would meet
the EU's excessive deficit procedure by 1996-97. The general government
deficit is then expected to be 2.25 per cent, below the 3 per cent of GDP
laid down in the Maastricht Treaty.
The new medium-term spending plans show general government expenditure,
excluding privatisation proceeds, declining over time as a share of GDP. The
Treasury said it showed 'real GGE growth over the next three years averaging
between 0.5 and 0.75 per cent per annum, well below the projected growth
rate of the economy'.
General government expenditure as a percentage of GDP is now expected to
fall from 43.5 per cent this year to 41 per cent in 1998-99. Tax revenues as
a share of GDP are predicted to rise from 37.25 per cent this year to 40 per
cent in 1999.
The rise in interest rates has raised the medium-term cost of servicing the
government debt. The Treasury said government debt interest would rise by a
third in the three years to 1996-97. After that it is expected to stablise
as borrowing is reduced, from Pounds 19.2bn to Pounds 26bn, and is expected
to stay at this level for several years.
</TEXT>
