<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (The Economy): Current account deficit 'to halve'
 -Trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK economic recoveries all too frequently run into the buffer of balance of
payments constraints.
There were plenty of people who forecast that the current recovery would end
in tears, as rapid consumption growth sucked in imports and a weakened UK
industrial base failed to compete in world export markets.
However, the Treasury is now forecasting that the current account deficit,
which was Pounds 10.3bn in 1993, will fall to Pounds 4bn in 1994 and to
Pounds 3.5bn in 1995.
This better performance, according to the Treasury, is due to the fact that
the improvement in the UK's cost competitiveness, which followed sterling's
departure from the Exchange Rate Mechanism, has been largely maintained. The
UK's cost competitiveness is estimated to be 10 per cent better than in the
second quarter of 1992.
With changes in UK unit labour costs predicted to be the same as those
overseas, the UK's current level of competitiveness will be broadly
maintained.
UK manufacturing exports are forecast to grow by 9.5 per cent in 1994 and by
8 per cent in 1995. Next year, stronger growth in Europe is expected to
replace weaker demand growth from North America.
Meanwhile, import growth has been more subdued than would have been
expected, given the pace of the recovery. Non-oil imports are expected to be
5.25 per cent higher in 1994 than in 1993 and to grow by 6 per cent next
year.
The balance of trade on visible goods is projected to move from a Pounds
13bn deficit in 1993 to a Pounds 9bn shortfall this year, and to Pounds
6.5bn in 1995. In addition, the surplus on invisible earnings is expected to
improve from Pounds 3bn in 1993 to Pounds 5bn in 1994, before falling back
to Pounds 3.5bn in 1995. Trade in oil has also contributed to the
improvement, with the oil surplus more than doubling between 1993 and 1994.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>ECON  Balance of trade.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
