<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (Their Budget): The rail controller
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Alastair Fyfe, 34: Duty control manager for European Passenger Services,
supervising running of trains on UK side of Channel Tunnel. Married with two
daughters aged three and one. Earns: Pounds 26,000. Has Pounds 80,000
mortgage.
Politics: Voted Scottish Nationalist in last election. Thinks he would vote
Lib-Dem now. Wanted: More spending on pre-school nurseries and tax breaks
for users of company supervised creches. More funds for NHS and public
transport and the creation of an integrated network of roads and railways.
Incentives to transfer freight from road to rail.
Said yesterday: 'Proposals to reduce the government's direct contribution to
rail spending represent a missed opportunity and show the government only
pays lip service to green policies. I was disappointed that no extra money
was made available for pre-school nursery facilities.
'I accept the need for some increase in car fuel duty though, as a country
dweller, I am happy the chancellor did not increase it by the higher amounts
called for by some commentators.'
