<DATE>941130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (News and Analysis): Something for everybody and
no harm done - Birmingham
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
West Midlands manufacturers gathered round the tea table in Birmingham heard
the chancellor out in silence. No exclamations of disgust, no chortles of
approbation.
'Our attitude summarises the effect he's likely to have,' said Mr Albert
Hargreaves, chairman of Apollo Metals, the aluminium processor and
distributor. Mr Rod Turner, managing director designate of Whale Tankers,
maker of waste disposal vehicles, said: 'My overall impression was that it
was a politician's gem of a budget: bits of something for everybody.'
'Nobody is violently outraged,' added Mr Jim Mundell, chairman of Woodcote
Industries, which manufactures forged components. 'The best thing for me was
the start on trying to reform the welfare system to encourage the unemployed
to seek work,' according to Mr Ed Kirk, the chairman of Frederick Cooper,
the metals finishing and architectural products company. 'It should help
companies like mine which are finding it difficult to fill the lower paid
jobs,' he added.
The issue here for the manufacturers was not whether they would receive tax
breaks. 'I don't think it's a question for the company. It's the incentive
for the individual - that's where the incentive should go. You've got to
have a better choice from the people available on the labour market. It's a
very important initiative,' Mr Mundell said of the chancellor's job creation
package.
'Imaginative,' agreed Mr Turner. 'I don't think it would give any employer
the incentive to take anybody on,' said Mr Hargreaves. That might not please
the chancellor.
What would please him was the general approval of his stance on corporate
taxation and his rejection of the demands from the CBI, the Engineering
Employers Federation and the Chambers of Commerce for changes in capital
allowances. Anticipating today's recriminations, Mr Mundell dismissed such
demands as 'part of the feel good factor - people holding off to see what
improvement there's going to be'.
Mr Kirk agreed. 'I wouldn't invest any money just because there's an
allowance,' he said. Mr Turner added: 'Anyway, it's driven by the leasing
companies. And the banks. They're the players in there.'
Mr Mundell said: 'There's been no investment in drop forging for 50 years.
You've really got to start again. The only way to re-equip is an industry
aid scheme.'
Pinioned between rising costs, like raw materials, which they have to
absorb, and downward pressure from their customers, the manufacturers
listened closely to what Mr Clarke said about inflation.
Mr Turner, sensing there was some sleight of hand in the calculation, said:
'One of the things that is disappointing - a target of 1 to 4 per cent for
inflation is pretty broad.'
'If they want to survive they've probably got to see the 4 rather than the
1,' Mr Mundell suggested, concerned about people's expectations of rising
wages and house prices.
Not that there is wage pressure at the moment. 'We have an American business
and they're not used to getting pay rises,' commented Mr Kirk.
'That's right. People get used to it,' said Mr Turner. 'I can't see a lot of
wage inflation coming,' Mr Kirk came back.
Mr Hargreaves has, however, seen the first signs. 'As you see people like
Jaguar and Rover raising their rates, we're seeing people moving on.'
'We have that problem but at the moment we can keep pulling people in,' said
Mr Kirk.
'That's all right if you haven't got 25 jobs you want to fill,' rejoined Mr
Hargreaves.
For Mr Kirk, the way to avoid cost pressures is to increase volumes. That
means, under current domestic conditions, the export markets. So Mr Clarke
got a pat on the back for reducing export guarantee premiums. And the
manufacturers went away into the gloom of the afternoon. 'No harm done,'
said Mr Mundell.
</TEXT>
