<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (News and Analysis): Labour delights in display of
wit and ridicule - Blair reaction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chancellor's speech was ridiculed by Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader,
as a Budget designed to quell divisions on the Conservative benches rather
than lay the groundwork for long-term economic recovery.
Mr Blair delighted Labour MPs in his first Budget response as Opposition
leader with a witty speech accusing the Tories of betraying election
promises, stealing Labour policies and financial sleight of hand.
It was a performance that appeared to discomfit cabinet ministers,
especially when Mr Blair accused the chancellor of exaggerating his
additional compensation package for the second stage of value added tax on
domestic fuel.
Mr Blair said that most of the VAT package had been announced last year or
reflected the normal increase in pensioners' benefits to compensate for
inflation. 'This will go down in history as the VAT-on-fuel Budget,' he
said.
'They (the Tories) fought the last election on the specific pledge that they
would not raise VAT. They have broken that promise and they will never be
trusted on tax again.'
As Labour MPs cheered, Mr Blair sought to increase Tory embarrassment over
divisions on Europe and VAT: 'We will challenge all members of the party
opposite - both parties opposite - to keep their promise to the electorate
upon which they were elected.
'If they break that promise, then the country has been warned that the
Conservative party put VAT on fuel and power when it promised it would not,
and it cannot be trusted not to put VAT on food, on children's clothing, on
books, on papers, if it is ever elected again.'
Mr Blair ridiculed the chancellor's picture of a strong economic recovery as
evidence that the government had become divorced from the reality of
everyday life.
He welcomed the chancellor's plans to cut tax avoidance and reduce
employers' National Insurance payments for the long-term unemployed
returning to the jobs market, which he claimed were policies pioneered by
Labour.
But he accused the chancellor of exaggerating the impact of his plans for
the Community Action scheme. He said the plans amounted to an increase on
last year's forecast, but a cut in the number of people benefiting from the
scheme.
Mr Blair provoked wry smiles on the Tory benches as he admitted that the
economy was improving but noted that voters were not giving the government
credit.
</TEXT>
