<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Budget 94 (News and Analysis): Making the economy work
better - At a glance guide
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FISCAL STANCE
The Budget is designed 'to ensure that the improvements in the public
finances announced in 1993 are delivered and to introduce further structural
reforms to make the economy work better'.
Spending squeezed
Government spending plans in 1995-96 to be reduced by Pounds 7.2bn, with
further reductions of Pounds 9bn in 1996-97, and Pounds 9.8bn in 1997-98.
This reflects a fall in the projected levels of inflation and government
savings.
The control total has been reduced to Pounds 249.6bn in 1994-1995, Pounds
1.3bn below the level announced last November in current prices.
The control total is forecast to rise to Pounds 255.7bn in 1995-1996, Pounds
6.9bn lower at current prices than last year's projections, and Pounds 0.5bn
lower in 1993-1994 prices. As a share of national output total government
spending is projected to fall from 44 per cent to 41 per cent over the three
years. Page 20
Limited tax changes
Tax changes in the Budget are relatively limited. Changes in income tax
reliefs and VAT announced last year and scheduled to come into place in
April next year will raise taxes by a further Pounds 2.75bn in 1995-96 and
Pounds 0.75bn in the following year.
This will be partly offset by measures to help businesses and the
unemployed, and ease the impact of the imposition of value added tax on
fuel. These will cost Pounds 1bn in 1995-96.
As a result, the total level of taxes received by the government is
projected to be Pounds 252.5bn in 1994-95, and rise to Pounds 278.9bn in the
following year.
Taxes and social security revenues as a proportion of GDP will rise from
33.75 per cent in 1993-1994 to 35.25 per cent in 1994-1995. Page 23
PSBR cut further
Public borrowing, including privatisation proceeds, is forecast to fall from
Pounds 34.4bn in 1994-95 to Pounds 21.5bn in 1995-96.
The public sector borrowing requirement is then projected to fall further,
to Pounds 13bn in 1996-97, Pounds 5bn in 1997-98, and then return to balance
at the end of the decade.
Consequently, the PSBR as a
proportion of gross domestic product is
forecast to fall to 5 per cent in 1994-95,
and then 3 per cent in 1995-96, and then 1.75 per cent in the following
year.
Page 20
SPENDING
Public sector pay and personnel
Tight controls to be maintained on public sector pay and government
departments to offset any increase in public sector pay next year by
increased efficiency. Total civil service numbers to fall to below 500,000
over the next four years.
Central government
Total central government costs to remain constant in cash terms for the next
four years, representing a 10 per cent fall, in real terms, in the cost of
government.
Local authorities
The 1995-96 total standard spending in the UK to be 2.2 per cent higher than
this year. Page 27
Social security
The rules covering housing benefit to be changed so that the cost of the
benefit will not be reimbursed to local authorities for rents that are
significantly higher than local averages.
The level of state support for mortgage payments in cases of sickness and
unemployment to be reduced.
Further initiatives against social security fraud, including the
introduction of electronic benefit payment systems in Post Offices. Page 27
Education
Education spending to be increased by almost 1 per cent in real terms next
year. Student grants and loans to increase in line with inflation. Page 27
Home Office
Spending on police to rise 3 per cent in 1995-96. Chief constables to be
given more control over their budgets. Further initiatives to attract
private investment into prisons. Page 26
Health
Health budget to increase by Pounds 1.3bn, or 1 per cent next year. This
follows an increase of 3.75 per cent in real terms this year as a result of
falling inflation. Further initiatives to attract private finance in health
construction pro-jects.
Transport
Public spending on motorways and trunk roads to be reduced significantly.
However efforts will be made to encourage further private-sector investment.
London Underground is expected to attract considerable private finance, as
well as Pounds 1bn of public investment in the next financial year. Page 27
Urban regeneration project
An extra Pounds 800m will be made available for new projects in deprived
urban areas in 1996-97. Page 26
MEASURES TO REDUCE UNEMPLOYMENT
Benefit system changes
Family Credit to be increased for people in full-time work. The payment of
housing benefit and Family Credit to be speeded up for people taking jobs.
Job-finding schemes such as Workwise to be extended. Experimental schemes
paying family credit to childless people to be introduced. Page 17
Employment tax changes
Employers who hire people who have been unemployed for more than two years
will be be exempt from National Insurance contributions for a year. Employer
National Insurance contributions for the low-paid to be reduced 0.6 per cent
a year from April 1995. Page 17
TAXES
Business taxation
No change to Advance Corporation Tax, Corporation Tax or Capital Allowances.
Recovery of VAT to be allowed on business lease car purchases.
Consultation paper announced on taxation of waste disposal in landfill, with
the aim of reducing employer National Insurance contributions. Further
measures to reduce tax-avoidance schemes on the issue of securities and the
buying of companies to utilise management expenses.
Small business support
Threshold for business VAT registration
to be increased to Pounds 46,000. Thirty per cent increase in threshold for
monthly PAYE payments for businesses, taking in two-thirds of all
businesses.
Business rates
Rises as a result of revaluation to be limited to a real 10 per cent for
large businesses/buildings and 7.5 per cent for small ones. Page 24
Export cover
ECGD credit insurance premiums to be reduced by 10 per cent. The limit for
cover for key developing markets to be raised by Pounds 300m in 1997-98.
Personal taxes
No change in 20 pence, 25 pence or 40 pence rates of income tax. Full
indexation of personal allowances and the threshold for higher rate tax.
Personal allowances for over 65s up Pounds 430 - Pounds 330 more than
indexation. The 20 pence lower band to be extended by further Pounds 200 to
Pounds 3,200. The capital gains tax exempt amount is increased from Pounds
5800 to Pounds 6000 a year. The inheritance tax threshold is increased from
Pounds 150,000 to Pounds 154,000.
Venture capital
Tax relief at 20 per cent on first Pounds 100,000 invested in venture
capital trusts, and tax-free dividends.
Amusement arcades
Amusement machines to be taxed in line with gaming machines.
Page 22
Tax exempt special savings accounts
(Tessas)
Tessas to be extended beyond their first expiry date of January 1996.
Investors who have held a Tessa for five years able to renew their account,
with tax-free interest on sums up to Pounds 9,000. Page 29
Personal equity plans (Peps)
Peps to be extended to cover not only investment in equity, but also
specified corporate bonds. Page 29
Taxes on spending:
No change in value-added tax.
VAT-on-fuel compensation package
Package of help cushioning effects of VAT
on fuel to be extended. The Home Energy Efficiency Scheme basket of grants
increases by Pounds 10m. Cold-weather payments rise to Pounds 8.50 per week
from Pounds 6 two years ago. Single pensioners will receive Pounds 52 more
in their retirement pensions as compensation for VAT on fuel while couples
will receive Pounds 73 beginning 1995-96. From April 1996 there will be
Pounds 68 extra on the single pensioner rate and Pounds 96 for pensioner
couples. People of working age cannot expect tax cuts or a reverse of taxes
already announced. Page 17
Fuel and vehicle taxes
Road fuel duties to increase by a real 5 per cent a year in future Budgets,
as announced last year. Petrol taxes to go up immediately by 2.5 pence a
litre for leaded and unleaded petrol. Tax on diesel to rise 3 pence a litre.
Vehicle excise duty on cars will rise by Pounds 5 to Pounds 135. Page 23
Tobacco and alcohol
Tobacco duties will continue to be increased by on average a real 3 per cent
a year, as announced last year. Tax on a packet of 20 cigarettes to be
increased by 10 pence. No change in the level of duties on beer, table wine
and spirits. Page 23
Tax avoidance
Measures to tighten some tax loopholes, including measures against the
avoidance of VAT through property transactions and
share issues, or operations with discounted securities.
THE FORECAST
Low inflation:
Underlying inflation expected to remain low. Target range remains 1-4 per
cent and is expected to fall to the lower half of this during the present
parliament. Underlying inflation is expected to reach a plateau at 2.5 per
cent next year, due to higher commodity prices and increasing profits, after
which it is expected to fall. Page 20
Stronger growth
GDP during 1994 will rise by over 4 per cent while the 1995 forecast
increases to 3.25 per cent from summer forecasts of 2.75 per cent for 1994
and 1995. The Treasury forecasts that the current account will improve
Pounds 6bn this year.
OPEN REPO MARKET
The Bank of England is to publish a consultative paper, on development of
open gilt repo market. Page 20
Compiled by Gillian Tett and Extel News
</TEXT>
