<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Norway 'faces a tough future': Brundtland warns of
difficulties in wake of No vote on EU
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY and KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Gro Harlem Brundtland, Norway's prime minister, said the country faced a
tough economic and political future yesterday after voting in a referendum
on Monday not to accept membership of the European Union.
'We are in a very serious situation,' she warned. 'It will now be more
demanding for us to reach our goals, more demanding to be heard
internationally . . . We will now have to work even harder to secure our
country and safeguard our welfare society.'
Norwegians rejected EU membership by a majority of 52.2 per cent to 47.8 per
cent, in spite of approval won in Austria, Finland and Sweden, its fellow
applicant countries. It was the second time Norway had turned its back on
Brussels, having voted No to membership of the European Economic Community
in 1972.
Most EU leaders expressed dismay at the result.
Denmark, Finland and Sweden had hoped for a strong Nordic front within the
EU. 'The weight of Nordic countries will be less within the EU for defending
the issues dear to us, like the protection of the enviroment and the fight
against unemployment,' said Mr Ingvar Carlsson, the Swedish prime minister.
A senior EU diplomat predicted that Norway would have to wait until the next
century for another chance to join the Union, probably at the same time as
the most advanced economies in central and eastern Europe. But the
Commission stressed that Norway's No would only mean technical adjustments
to the accession treaties negotiated earlier this year, and there would be
no need to delay enlargement to 15 members.
Mr Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, said the No result
would affect the future status of the European Economic Area, the halfway
house for members of the European Free Trade Association leading to full EU
membership.
Mrs Brundtland said a priority for her minority Labour government was to
ensure that the EEA remained intact. The accord, giving non-EU members
access to the EU internal market, now applies only to Norway, Iceland and
Liechtenstein.
Financial markets reacted calmly to the vote, as they had mainly discounted
a No result. But the result provoked a chorus of dismay and concern from
Norwegian business.
Mr Rolf Saether, chief executive of the Norwegian Shipowners Association,
said the outcome had created 'serious uncertainty'. Norske Skog, the
country's biggest forestry products company, said it now had a weaker
position than its Swedish and Finnish competitors.
Country that went out into the cold, Page 2
