<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Nuclear Electric sale hope recedes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Executives at Nuclear Electric, the state-owned power utility, are close to
abandoning hopes that the company can be privatised before the next
election.
In spite of confident statements at the company's interim results
presentation yesterday, executives concede privately that the chances of a
sell-off being agreed as part of the government's nuclear review are small
and declining.
One executive said: 'Unless there is a significant change in government
thinking in the next few weeks, there will not be enough time for ministers
to steer through privatisation before an election.'
However, the company is still hoping that the government will accede to its
request for a restructuring of the business, with perhaps the Magnox
stations being hived off into a separate company.
That would increase the chances of privatisation of the rest of the business
later in the decade. The review is expected to leave open the possibility of
this happening.
In the six months to September 30, Nuclear Electric made an operating loss
of Pounds 126m (Pounds 118m a year earlier) before adding the nuclear levy
on consumers. With the levy, operating profits rose Pounds 2m to Pounds
499m.
Part of the reason for the flat performance was the cap on prices in the
electricity pool which Nuclear Electric estimates will reduce profits by
about Pounds 100m this year, mostly in the first half. The cap was also
responsible for an 11 per cent fall in turnover to Pounds 779m.
Mr John Collier, chairman, said the company was showing its underlying
strength by maintaining its forecast of being profitable before the levy
next year in spite of the effects of the pool cap.
He said the company had reduced unit costs by 8 per cent to 3p during the
half year and achieved record productivity, up 20 per cent. It had also
become the second-largest generator for the first time in any half year by
capturing 25.2 per cent of the market, up from 23.3 per cent in the first
six months of 1993-94.
Mr Bob Hawley, chief executive, said PowerGen could overtake it for the full
year but next year Nuclear Electric could be back in the number two position
because of the forthcoming full commissioning of Sizewell B.
Manpower fell 57 to 9,397 during the six months. Mr Hawley said the company
was on target to become the lowest-cost generator by 1997.
Mr Collier said the company's case for privatisation lay at the heart of its
submission to the nuclear review. 'Whether it happens, how or when it
happens, is of course strictly a matter for our shareholder.' But Nuclear
Electric was poised to be another privatisation success story.
The chairman said the company would only build Sizewell C, the planned
station on the Suffolk coast, if it added to shareholder value. The company
believed it would be possible to fund the station entirely in the private
sector.
Mr Hawley said there were grounds for optimism on contract negotiations with
BNFL, the reprocessing company.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Nuclear Electric.
</CO>
