<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Carsberg anticipates a return to his roots: John Ridding on
why the OFT chief is resigning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sipping wine in the French economy ministry, Sir Bryan Carsberg appeared
relaxed yesterday about his decision to resign as director-general of
Britain's Office of Fair Trading.
'There is less to it than meets the eye,' he said, referring to his move to
head the International Accounting Standards Committee. 'It is not because of
problems in my present job. I haven't had a row with ministers or anything
like that. The move is entirely because I was offered a job which I want to
do.'
In Paris for a meeting on international competition policy, Sir Bryan
described his move - which will take effect in six months - as a natural
progression. 'Accounting and accounting standards are a central theme of my
career,' he said, referring to his academic experience in accountancy and
the three years he spent with the Financial Accounting Standards Board in
the US between 1978 and 1981. It was only in March last year that he left
the British Accounting Standards Board.
For Sir Bryan, his next step is consistent with the job he is doing now.
'The more the idea of free trade becomes internationally accepted, the more
desirable it will be to have convergence on competition policy. For global
competition policy we need common accounting standards.'
During the next six months, however, it will be business as usual. At the
top of the agenda is the sensitive issue of the rival bids from British
Aerospace and GEC for control of VSEL, the warship builder. Sir Bryan will
not be drawn on a decision on referring the proposals to the government.
On the subject of UK competition policy, Sir Bryan appears largely
satisfied. He defends the establishment of bodies to monitor competition in
newly privatised utilities.
According to Sir Bryan, however, further steps are needed in competition
policy. One concerns the restrictive trade practices law. Under the present
system, no trading practice is automatically prohibited. A review is
required to determine whether cartels or other practices are in the public
interest.
A second reform proposed by Sir Bryan involves a toughening of the Fair
Trading Act. He says there is a case to extend provisions against so-called
'rogue traders' - who have broken either criminal or civil law - to other
malpractices that do not necessarily break the law.
</TEXT>
