<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Best Travel goes into liquidation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Best Travel, the UK's seventh-largest tour operator, went into liquidation
last night. It was the travel industry's biggest collapse since Mr Harry
Goodman's International Leisure Group failed in 1991.
Plans by Airtours, the second-largest tour operator, to purchase Best
Travel's brand names failed yesterday. Mr Nick Lyle of accountants Touche
Ross, who were appointed liquidators, last night strongly criticised the
Association of British Travel Agents for what he alleged was its failure to
ensure that at least some of the Best Travel business was saved.
The Civil Aviation Authority said the collapse would not affect the 3,000
Best Travel holidaymakers currently abroad. The company has a Pounds 14m
bond, which will be used to repatriate customers abroad and ensure those who
have booked holidays are compensated.
Although rumours about the health of Best Travel had been circulating for
weeks, the first firm indication of trouble came yesterday morning when
Ambassador Airways, the company's airline, was put into liquidation and its
fleet of six Boeing aircraft grounded.
Mr Lyle said the aircraft had played a significant part in dragging the rest
of the company down. He said the cash requirements of the airline during the
winter months would have been high.
Mr Lyle said he was instructed on Saturday to try to find a buyer for Best
Travel. He approached large tour operators over the weekend and found
Airtours the most positive.
He said an agreement was reached that Airtours would buy Best Travel's two
brand names, Cypriana and Grecian Holidays. Mr Lyle said that while this
would not have saved Best Travel itself or the airline, it would have
ensured that customers who had booked holidays could continue to go on them.
Airtours' payment for the brands would also have increased the amount
available for Best Travel creditors. Mr Lyle said the amount would have been
'several million pounds'.
He said, however, that when the deal was taken to Abta for its approval, the
association replied that it could not reach enough members of its Tour
Operators' Council yesterday. Abta said the council would be meeting
tomorrow. Mr Lyle said, however, that this was too late and Best Travel went
into liquidation.
He said: 'The whole transaction has been frustrated by the unresponsive
approach of the people who regulate the travel industry.' Airtours declined
to comment.
Abta agreed that it had told Airtours yesterday that it would not be able to
reach enough members of the 20-member Tour Operators' Council to reach a
decision. The association added, however, that Airtours did not require the
council's approval to purchase the brands. All Abta could do was decide
whether holidays sold under the brands would be accepted into its
jurisdiction.
Following the introduction of new consumer protection laws, Abta no longer
has the power to prevent companies selling holidays which fall outside its
jurisdiction.
</TEXT>
