<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Cuts in job loss payments unlawful
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Employment Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government deductions from protective awards to redundant workers were
declared unlawful yesterday by an industrial tribunal.
In the first successful challenge to the Department of Employment's policy
of cutting payments to redundant workers, 1,500 workers who lost their jobs
at the Swan Hunter shipyard will receive extra money as a result.
The Newcastle upon Tyne tribunal has also referred two other issues raised
in the case to the European Court of Justice. These cover the government's
policy of restricting protective awards to a maximum of eight weeks and
limiting a week's pay to Pounds 205.
'This decision will affect thousands of workers made redundant in other
industries,' said Mr Stefan Cross, the solicitor representing Swan Hunter
workers.
The Department of Employment said the case raised complex issues concerning
linkages between UK law and European Union directives.
</TEXT>
