<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Blow for Names over cover ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyd's underwriters being sued for alleged negligence yesterday won the
right not to reveal the total amount of insurance cover available to meet
claims against them.
The Court of Appeal ruled that while the underwriters' insurers should
disclose to Names the wording of relevant 'errors and omissions' policies,
they should not have to reveal the extent of their total cover or the
premiums paid.
The ruling is a setback for some Names who could have used the information
to improve the strategies of their legal campaigns. Full disclosure of the
sums available for damages claims could also have acted as a catalyst for
possible out-of-court settlements.
The Court of Appeal partially overturned an order made by Mr Justice
Phillips, the trial judge for the Gooda Walker and Feltrim actions, that the
insurers should make full disclosure of the details of their cover to help
the courts decide how damages should best be paid.
At the centre of the issue is the acknowledgement by all involved that the
total damages claimed against underwriters - thought to approach Pounds 3bn
 -might considerably exceed the amount of insurance cover available.
Following the victory of the Gooda Walker Names, who won damages initially
estimated at Pounds 504m, the courts have begun considering how best the
damages should be paid.
Mr Justice Phillips had been considering whether damages should be paid on a
'first come first served basis' - with the Gooda Walker Names heading the
queue - or on another basis intended to spread damages among all successful
Names, no matter when their cases come to court.
Giving judgment, Lord Justice Saville said the insurers should not have to
disclose the total amount of their cover since this was not relevant as a
matter of law.
However, he continued: 'I do so with regret for it seems to me that in the
circumstances of the Lloyd's litigation, there is much to be said for the
view that the sooner the parties know where they stand as regards likely
recoveries at the end of the road, the sooner and cheaper will be the
resolution of this litigation, which can only be for the benefit of all.'
Clyde &amp; Co, solicitors acting for the errors and omissions insurers, said a
figure for the total cover available would anyway have been 'misleading'.
It would not have corresponded to the cover available for individual claims
against particular Lloyd's agencies.
In a statement, Clyde &amp; Co said the insurers were 'firmly convinced' that
the insurance cover for damages awarded to Gooda Walker Names would be
'significantly less' than was available under the Lloyd's settlement offer
rejected by Names earlier this year.
It also revealed that at the time of the settlement offer Names' action
groups - including the Gooda Walker action group - had been offered the
chance to verify, on a confidential basis, the level of errors and omissions
cover available. The Gooda Walker group had not taken up that offer, Clyde &amp;
Co said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Lloyd's of London.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9211 Courts.
</IN>
