<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Trade gap cut in Australia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A better export performance caused Australia's trade deficit to narrow last
month, bringing relief to the Keating government and lessening chances of
another interest rate rise before Christmas. Latest figures showed a current
account deficit for October of ADollars 1.65bn (Pounds 750m), seasonally
adjusted, higher than the ADollars 1.27bn in October 1993, but below the
deficits of ADollars 1.8bn and ADollars 2.1bn in September and August this
year.
Exports rose 5 per cent seasonally adjusted in October, with commodities
such as gold, wool and coal contributing strongly. Imports, on the same
basis, were 2 per cent higher. Economists had been predicting an October
deficit of ADollars 1.8bn-ADollars 1.9bn. As the prospect of a further early
interest rate rise ebbed, the Australian dollar drifted lower.
A sharp decline in building approvals last month suggested the recent
housing boom has peaked. Figures for business investment were more
complicated; new capital expenditure for the quarter declined overall, but
spending on plant and equipment was 3.4 per cent higher (27.6 per cent above
that seen a year ago). Mr Ralph Willis, treasurer, claimed there was 'a
continuing strong recovery in business investment'.
Attention will now shift to the September quarter's GDP figures, to be
released today and expected to show growth running at 5.5 per cent
annualised. Mr Bernie Fraser, governor of the Reserve Bank, said the
government should consider raising taxes to cut its budget deficit and
warned that lack of wage restraint would mean higher interest rates.
</TEXT>
