<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Japan's unemployment rate stubbornly refuses to fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's jobless rate hovered at 3 per cent for the fourth month running in
October, as a fall in manufacturing jobs was absorbed by a rise in service
sector workers, reports William Dawkins from Tokyo.
The unemployment rate's refusal to decline from its seven-year high of 1.99m
marks a potentially disturbing break with previous, job-creating recoveries.
In earlier economic upturns, unemployment started to fall six to 12 months
after the first signs of recovery, according to the government's Economic
Planning Agency. Yet the agency believes the recession touched bottom in
October last year, 13 months ago. This requires careful monitoring, said Mr
Manso Hamamoto, labour minister.
The number of job offers for every 100 applicants also stagnated in October
at 64, for the second month in a row, well under half the number of jobs per
applicant two years ago.
This ratio is likely to stay low, because of a backlog of new graduates,
which pushed up the number of applicants by 7.7 per cent in the year to
October, much faster than the 1.5 per cent rise in the number of job offers.
Total employment was almost stable at 64.8m workers, within which the
manufacturing workforce fell by 3.3 per cent year on year, the sharpest drop
since April 1987. This is a sign manufacturing industry is continuing to
shed workers through a freeze on recruitment and failure to replace retired
staff. Service sector jobs rose 1.6 per cent over the same period.
</TEXT>
