<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Beating the slump and the yen: A Japanese company's export
route to survival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In Katsuta city, just north of Tokyo, the head office of Suzuki
Manufacturing, a medium-sized maker of printed circuit boards, is buzzing
with activity.
The brisk pace of business Suzuki has seen over the past two years contrasts
with many of its fellow manufacturers in the industrial heartland of Ibaraki
Prefecture. The region is dominated by subcontractors that have long
depended on jobs created by Hitachi, Japan's largest electric machinery
maker, and its group companies.
As Japan's economic slump and the 24 per cent appreciation of the yen
against the dollar have squeezed profits at Hitachi, many of the region's
smaller companies are finding themselves having to look elsewhere for work.
Unlike the majority of suppliers in the region which have suffered from
tying their fortunes too closely to a Japanese parent company, which in turn
has been hurt by the high yen, Suzuki is riding a wave of success by
exporting most of its output.
Indeed, over the past several years Suzuki (no relation of Suzuki Motor) has
reduced its dependence on Japanese customers and in spite of the high yen
environment has been able to sell 99 per cent of what it makes to overseas
customers.
'In the home market business began to drop off about two years ago,' says Ms
Man Ling Chang, manager of the overseas sales section. 'There is no business
in Japan,' she says.
While demand in Japan has dried up, Suzuki has been able to take advantage
of strong demand overseas, specifically for the printed circuit boards for
cellular phones that the company specialises in. Its main customers include
world-famous names in the cellular phones market such as Motorola of the US
and Sweden's Ericsson.
The company's success in supplying overseas customers has been such that at
a time when the majority of internationally active Japanese companies have
embarked on wide-ranging rationalisation measures and have shifted
production to lower-cost countries, Suzuki has not had to cut its workforce
nor move production overseas.
'We manufacture everything in Japan,' proclaims Mr Yoshihiro Koyama,
director of Suzuki's Sawa plant.
Suzuki has found strong overseas demand even in the high-yen environment
because it had a product and technology that few others in the world can
provide. The specialised printed circuit board it makes through a demanding
process 'is something that can be made in no other Asian country yet', says
Ms Chang.
Four years ago, the company had a very different structure. Then, Suzuki
made hard disk drives and printed circuit boards for computers and 50 per
cent of its business came from domestic customers.
These products, however, have low value added and are price competitive.
Prices in the hard disk drive market, for example, are negotiated four times
a year, Mr Koyama says.
With the yen's appreciation Japanese makers of hard disk drives and PCBs for
computers have been devastated by competitors in Taiwan and Korea, where
labour costs are one-third those in Japan.
Suzuki Manufacturing avoided the fate of many in the industry by shifting
quickly to higher value-added PCBs for the cellular phone market. The speed
with which it acted on that decision has given it a lead in a market that is
surging on the back of growing demand for cellular phones in industrialised
markets.
Suzuki's management also had the foresight to look outside Japan for growth
at an early stage, rather than follow the common Japanese practice of
targetting the home market first.
It helped that Mr Katsuzo Suzuki, president, began building business ties in
the US, where he had studied, long before the yen rose above Y100 to the
dollar.
The latest corporate results from Japanese companies indicate that many
Japanese companies much larger than Suzuki Manufacturing have likewise
benefited from the strength of demand overseas.
In the electronics industry, for instance, manufacturers from NEC to Sharp,
have been able to report improved profits thanks in large part to strong
demand for semiconductors and liquid crystal display panels triggered by the
buoyant US and south-east Asian economies. Japanese motor companies have
also been helped by the strength of the US economy.
The shift to a higher value-added product is not enough to beat the impact
of the yen's appreciation, Mr Koyama says. To remain competitive against
Korean and Taiwanese manufacturers it is necessary to make higher
value-added products in volume, he says.
With the yen's rise forcing many companies to move production overseas,
'Japan's manufacturing industry is in chaos', Mr Koyama says.
But if the example of Suzuki Manufacturing is anything to go by, the
challenge presented by the yen's appreciation is forcing many Japanese
manufacturers to become even more competitive than ever.
</TEXT>
