<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Italian prime minister Mr Silvio Berlusconi last night headed off a break
with his coalition partner, the populist Northern League, by winning limited
approval for a document outlining the main objectives of the six-month-old
right-wing coalition. The move followed threats by Mr Umberto Bossi, the
League leader, to pull out of the coalition once the 1995 budget had passed
through parliament. The document, prepared by Mr Berlusconi over the weekend
and presented at yesterday's cabinet meeting, centred on plans to create a
more decentralised administrative structure, deferring to the League's
demands for greater federalism. Other elements included acceleration of the
reform of public administration, a shake-up of the justice system and the
introduction of anti-trust laws to avoid the prime minister's conflict of
interest with his Fininvest business empire. The cabinet session also gave
Mr Berlusconi authority to negotiate an agreement on pensions with the trade
unions - but keeping reform of the pension system inside the 1995 budget
legislation. The talks with the unions will be held today in an effort to
avert their plan for a general strike on Friday in protest against the
budget.
