<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 94 / Tory ranks pin hopes on tax cuts before election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ministers and Tory MPs last night grasped at the prospect of income tax cuts
before the general election as Mr Kenneth Clarke's Budget drew a respectful
but less than ecstatic reception on the government backbenches.
The deep cuts in spending announced by the chancellor - and the parallel
falls in his projections for public borrowing - raised the morale of a party
battered by the latest infighting over Europe.
But Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, signalled that the opposition would
next week try to kindle a Tory backbench rebellion over the imposition of
full rate value added tax on domestic fuel.
Mr Clarke's emphasis on restoring order to public finances, building
confidence in the economic recovery and reviving work incentives for the
unemployed were applauded by senior Conservatives as a sensible medium-term
strategy.
The chancellor enhanced his reputation as a politician with the confidence
to shrug off short-term expediency and to plan for the medium term.
Amid widespread fears, however, that the Budget would do little to boost the
government's popularity in the short term, other cabinet ministers suggested
that its success would depend on reinforcing discipline on the back benches.
Senior ministers are resigned to a crushing defeat in next-month's Dudley
by-election, a result that might add impetus to a threatened Conservative
revolt over VAT on domestic fuel.
Mr Clarke's announcement of help for the elderly to meet the costs of the
increase in the tax from 8 per cent to 17.5 per cent in April failed to
dispel disquiet over the rise among the government's supporters.
After confirmation yesterday that eight Tory MPs had been suspended from the
parliamentary party after Monday's revolt on Europe and that a ninth had
resigned the Conservative whip, Mr Major signalled he wanted to avoid
another confrontation.
In spite of the chancellor's insistence that the VAT increase was an
essential part of his overall tax measures, Mr Major refused to elevate it
into an issue of confidence.
His enemies on the right of the party appeared unable last night to muster
sufficient support to mount a challenge before today's deadline for a
contest. Nevertheless, ministers remain in doubt as to whether the
government will be able to delay an election until 1997.
Meanwhile, rightwing hopes that the government will seek to bridge Tory
divisions by agreeing to a referendum on further European integration were
boosted by Mr Jonathan Aitken, the Treasury chief secretary.
In a Budget interview, Mr Aitken said a decision to join a single European
currency would prompt a decision on whether to use 'the normal channels of
parliamentary democracy, or whether we should go to a referendum'.
VAT revolt threat, Page 17
</TEXT>
